{"parse":{"title":"The History of White People","pageid":30400937,"revid":857994522,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">The History of White People <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+History+of+White+People&amp;rft.author=%5B%5BNell+Irvin+Painter%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BW.+W.+Norton+%26+Company%5D%5D&amp;rft.pages=496\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:The_history_of_white_people_bookcover.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"The history of white people bookcover.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/The_history_of_white_people_bookcover.jpg/220px-The_history_of_white_people_bookcover.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"333\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4c/The_history_of_white_people_bookcover.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"264\" data-file-height=\"400\" /></a><div>Cover of the first edition</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Nell_Irvin_Painter\" title=\"Nell Irvin Painter\">Nell Irvin Painter</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Country</th><td>\nUnited States</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\nEnglish</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Published</th><td>\n2010</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/W._W._Norton_%26_Company\" title=\"W. W. Norton &amp; Company\">W. W. Norton &amp; Company</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Media&#160;type</th><td>\nPrint (<a href=\"/wiki/Hardcover\" title=\"Hardcover\">Hardcover</a>)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Pages</th><td>\n496</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a></th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0393049343\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0393049343\">978-0393049343</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>The History of White People</b></i> is a 2010 book by <a href=\"/wiki/Nell_Irvin_Painter\" title=\"Nell Irvin Painter\">Nell Irvin Painter</a>, in which the author explores the idea of <a href=\"/wiki/Whiteness_studies\" title=\"Whiteness studies\">whiteness</a> throughout history, beginning with ancient Greece and continuing through the beginning of <a href=\"/wiki/Scientific_racism\" title=\"Scientific racism\">scientific racism</a> in early modern Europe to 19th- through 21st-century America.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Overview\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Overview</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Reception\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reception</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Sources\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sources</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Overview\">Overview</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_History_of_White_People&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Overview\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The book describes attitudes toward and definitions of race among Europeans, and particularly Americans of European descent. The author says the idea of race is not just a matter of biology but also includes \"concepts of labor, gender, class, and images of personal beauty\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The earliest European societies, including the Greeks and Romans, had no concept of race and classified people by ethnicity and social class, with the lowest class being slaves.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Throughout most of European history, slaves were generally of European origin, often from conquered countries. From the fifth to the eleventh century the Vikings were especially prolific slavers, capturing and selling the inhabitants wherever they went.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> It was only in relatively modern times that slavery became associated with race. In 1790 U.S. citizens were defined as \"free white men\"; this excluded white men who were <a href=\"/wiki/Indentured_servants\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Indentured servants\">indentured servants</a>. By the mid 19th century in America, white people (as then defined) were all free; slaves were of African or part-African descent.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>When writers and scientists began to explore the concept of race, they focused on Europe, describing three or four different races among Europeans. Much of the classification was done by head shape and skull measurements, as well as height and skin pigmentation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The most attractive and most admirable race was that found in northwestern Europe, while the inhabitants of eastern and southern Europe were classified as lower races. The categorizing of different European races had legal and social effects in the United States, where 19th century immigrants from less favored areas such as Ireland, Italy, and Iberia were treated as less than fully \"white\" for legal and social purposes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>During the 19th and early 20th centuries in the United States, discussion of race often included a belief in the permanent superiority of one racial group over others, and a fear of the loss of racial purity. Intelligence testing was widely used as a means of ranking various races and ethnicities; this led to immigration laws that encouraged immigration from the presumably most desirable racial and ethnic groups while discouraging or forbidding others.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Ralph_Waldo_Emerson\" title=\"Ralph Waldo Emerson\">Ralph Waldo Emerson</a> was an influential figure in promoting some of these racial theories.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Eugenics became a widely discussed issue and was embraced to some extent by many prominent people including <a href=\"/wiki/Theodore_Roosevelt\" title=\"Theodore Roosevelt\">Theodore Roosevelt</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>  and <a href=\"/wiki/David_Starr_Jordan\" title=\"David Starr Jordan\">David Starr Jordan</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>. Eugenics proponents urged higher reproductive rates among the most desirable population and sometimes sterilization of the less desirable elements.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The author traces four consecutive \"enlargements of American whiteness\" by which Irish, Italians, Jews, Hispanics, and other discriminated-against ethnicities gradually became fully accepted into white society. The passage of the <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964\" title=\"Civil Rights Act of 1964\">Civil Rights Act of 1964</a> eliminated legal discrimination by race. As of the book's publication date, 2010, mixed-race people were more common and were becoming integrated: \"The dark of skin who happen to be rich ... and the light of skin from any (racial background) who are beautiful, are now well on their way to inclusion.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> The author concludes that race has not disappeared from American society - \"the fundamental black/white binary endures\" - but the \"category of whiteness - or we might say more precisely, a category of nonblackness - effectively expands.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reception\">Reception</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_History_of_White_People&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Reception\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The book was a New York Times best seller.<sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Paul Devlin, writing in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/San_Francisco_Chronicle\" title=\"San Francisco Chronicle\">San Francisco Chronicle</a></i>, said the book \"is perhaps the definitive story of a most curious adjective. It is a scholarly, non-polemical masterpiece of broad historical synthesis, combining political, scientific, economic and cultural history.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Devlin_17-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Devlin-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> Linda Gordon of <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i> says the book \"has much to teach everyone, including whiteness experts, but it is accessible and breezy, its coverage broad and therefore necessarily superficial.\" She adds that she wishes she had had this book, \"an insightful and lively exposition\", to help her teach undergraduate students about race theory.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Thomas Rogers in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Salon_(magazine)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Salon (magazine)\">Salon</a></i> calls it an \"exhaustive and fascinating new look at the history of the idea of the white race\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-18\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_History_of_White_People&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. <i>xi</i>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. <i>xi</i>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, pp. 34&#8211;35. </span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 201.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, pp. 215&#8211;6.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 206.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 204.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-NYT-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-NYT_8-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-NYT_8-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a href=\"/wiki/Linda_Gordon\" title=\"Linda Gordon\">Gordon, Linda</a> (March 25, 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/28/books/review/Gordon-t.html?_r=4&amp;pagewanted=all\">\"Who's White?\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Who%E2%80%99s+White%3F&amp;rft.date=2010-03-25&amp;rft.aulast=Gordon&amp;rft.aufirst=Linda&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2010%2F03%2F28%2Fbooks%2Freview%2FGordon-t.html%3F_r%3D4%26pagewanted%3Dall&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+History+of+White+People\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Devlin, Paul (March 28, 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-03-28/books/19913585_1_whiteness-cultural-history-nell-irvin-painter\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">'</span>The History of White People<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">'</span>\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/San_Francisco_Chronicle\" title=\"San Francisco Chronicle\">San Francisco Chronicle</a></i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=San+Francisco+Chronicle&amp;rft.atitle=%27The+History+of+White+People%27&amp;rft.date=2010-03-28&amp;rft.aulast=Devlin&amp;rft.aufirst=Paul&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farticles.sfgate.com%2F2010-03-28%2Fbooks%2F19913585_1_whiteness-cultural-history-nell-irvin-painter&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+History+of+White+People\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Sanneh, Kelefa (April 12, 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/books/2010/04/12/100412crbo_books_sanneh?currentPage=all\">\"Beyond the Pale\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_Yorker\" title=\"The New Yorker\">The New Yorker</a></i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+Yorker&amp;rft.atitle=Beyond+the+Pale&amp;rft.date=2010-04-12&amp;rft.aulast=Sanneh&amp;rft.aufirst=Kelefa&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Farts%2Fcritics%2Fbooks%2F2010%2F04%2F12%2F100412crbo_books_sanneh%3FcurrentPage%3Dall&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+History+of+White+People\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 253.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-12\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-12\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 265&#8211;6.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-13\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-13\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 273&#8211;7.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-14\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-14\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 389&#8211;90.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-15\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-15\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Painter 2010, p. 396.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-16\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-16\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/nell-irvin-painter/\">\"Nell Irvin Painter\"</a>. <i>The New York Review of Books</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">17 June</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Review+of+Books&amp;rft.atitle=Nell+Irvin+Painter&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nybooks.com%2Fcontributors%2Fnell-irvin-painter%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+History+of+White+People\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Devlin-17\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Devlin_17-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Devlin, Paul (March 28, 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.sfgate.com/books/article/The-History-of-White-People-3194794.php\">\"The History o